category=Getting Started
description=<p>This example shows you how to populate a menu with a list of available on the current system.  You may want to do this if your application has a Font menu, as you can't tell ahead of time which fonts the user might have installed, so you need to check the fonts at run time.</p>
discussion=<p>This custom command is used with the following statement:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  createFontMenu</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>It assumes that there is already a button called &quot;Font&quot;. Usually this button will be part of a group of buttons that makes up a menu bar. Remember that in Revolution, menus are implemented as buttons, and a menu bar is a group of menu buttons. The list of fonts is placed in the button, and each line of the button contents becomes a separate menu item when the menu is displayed.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The handler first uses <font face="Courier" size="11">the fontNames</font> function to obtain a list of installed fonts. Since the list may not be returned in alphabetical order, the handler next sorts the list. Finally, it puts the list into the button's contents.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>You would probably use the &quot;createFontMenu&quot; custom command in your application's startup handler, as part of setting up and initializing the application.</p>
level=2
licensed=false
name=Placing a font list into a menu
solution=<p><font color="#980517">on</font> createFontMenu</p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">get</font> the <font color="#F88017">fontNames</font> <font color="#68228B">-- list of installed fonts</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">sort</font> lines of it</p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">put</font> it into button &quot;Font&quot;</p>\n<p><font color="#980517">end</font> createFontMenu</p>
title=Placing a font list into a menu